Ioannina, 30 May 2019

SMDX data

SDMX, which stands for Statistical Data and Metadata eXchange is an international initiative that aims at standardising and modernising (“industrialising”) the mechanisms and processes for the exchange of statistical data and metadata among international organisations and their member countries

Eurostat, OECD, UN, World Bank, IMF and many others use SDMX in order to transit their datasets.

Using R one can handle these datasets either with the rsdmx library or with specific APIs, like the eurostat library: https://ropengov.github.io/eurostat/

Data download

Every dataset from Eurostat can be defined by a unique name. We just need to provide this name to the API, for example:

library(tidyverse)

Eurostat distributed datasets

Eurostat has to collect, process and distribute:

  • values for something (for example internet usage)
  • for several countries or regions of countries
  • for several times (yearly, quertely or monthly data)

With a common and stable format

  • as time passes by
  • as new countries enter
  • some countries might go

Disadvantages

  • Dirty data
  • Need some data cleaning before processing
  • Mixes data with descriptions
  • Separate coluns for each year!

but:

What You See is What You Get

SMDX data storage and use

Of course, we do not store datasets in this format.

So, there is no reason to use them in this format.

Forget Excel files and use directly SDMX tables. It’s Easy!

  • Locations (countries, regions and etc) are stored in one single column: geo
  • Time (years, quarters, months, etc) are stored in one sigle column: time is ISO format (YYYY-MM-DD)
  • Values (of anything) are stored in one single column: values
  • Other characteristics are stored in separate columns
  • The triplet (geo, time, values) is common everywhere

That’s easy!

INSERT, DELETE, UPDATE data

  • If we have to add a new value, we have to INSERT a row
  • If we have to delete a value, we DELETE a row
  • If we have to update a value, we UPDATE a row

This rowwise procedure, very similar to relational databases and SQL is essential.

We do not perform these actions to the actual data sets, we ARE NOT the Eurostat data administrators.

But as we DO data management and analysis we have to do it sometimes.

So, in every dataset:

  • Every column is a variable
  • Every row is an observation

Employment in high- and medium-high technology manufacturing and knowledge-intensive services

This is the SDI 9.2

Let’s compare Greece with Germany and UK and guess why young Greek scientists emigrate

sdg_09_20 %>% 
  filter(nace_r2 == 'C_HTC_MH') %>% 
  filter(geo %in% c('EL', 'DE', 'UK')) %>% 
  mutate(lbl = if_else(time == max(time), as.character(Country), NA_character_)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = time, y = values, colour = Country)) +
  geom_line(size = 1.2) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(2006, 2018, by = 2)) +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, 12), breaks = seq(0, 12, by = 2)) + 
  geom_label_repel(aes(label = label), nudge_x = 1, nudge_y = 1, na.rm = TRUE) +
  theme_economist() +
  theme(text = element_text(size = 16)) +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

A map

Employment in high- and medium-high technology manufacturing and knowledge-intensive services

SHP0 <- read_rds("../data/SHP0.rds")

DF <- sdg_09_20 %>% 
  inner_join(SHP0, by = "geo") %>% 
  st_as_sf %>% 
  filter(nace_r2 == 'C_HTC_MH') %>% 
  filter(time == 2018) 

myPal  <- colorNumeric(palette = "Blues",  domain = c(0, DF$values))
LABELS <- paste0("<h3>", DF$Country, " : ", DF$values, "%</h3>") %>% 
  lapply(HTML)

DF %>% 
  leaflet() %>% 
  setView(lng = 12.25, lat = 51.34, zoom = 4) %>% 
  addPolygons(weight = 1, color = "white",
              fillColor = ~myPal(values), fillOpacity = 0.9, label = LABELS) %>% 
  addLegend("topright", pal = myPal, values = ~values, title = "% of employment") %>% 
  addControl(html = "<small>(C) EuroGeographics for the administrative boundaries</small>", 
             position = "bottomleft")

Renewable energy

REN - SDMX data

SDMX data

  • Only one column with values
  • time indicator for time (yearly/monthly/quartely, etc) in ISO, character or numeric format
  • geo indicator for Countries/Regions/Locations
  • othe indicator in other columns:
    • unit, here PC means percentage (other units might apply, see metadata)
    • nrg_bal, sector of the economy

Reminder

  • geo, time, values are common everywhere
  • other data columns are case dependent

REN - 2018

Share (%) of renewable energy in gross final energy consumption by sector, here all sectors are taken into consideration.

sdg_07_40 <- read_rds("../data/sdg_07_40.rds")
sdg_07_40 %>% 
  inner_join(EU, by = "geo") %>% 
  filter(nrg_bal == 'REN' & time == 2017) %>% 
  arrange(values) %>% 
  mutate(Country = factor(Country, Country)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Country, y = values)) +
  geom_col(fill = "#41AB5D", width = 0.2) +
  geom_point(color = "#41AB5D", size = 2) + 
  labs(title = "Reweable energy share (%)", x = "", y = "") +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, 60), breaks = seq(0, 60, 10)) +
  coord_flip() +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(panel.border = element_blank()) +
  theme(panel.grid.minor = element_blank()) +
  theme(panel.grid.major.y = element_blank()) +
  theme(text = element_text(size = 10))

REN - One country over time, the case of Poland

sdg_07_40 %>%
  filter(nrg_bal == 'REN') %>% 
  filter(geo %in% c('PL')) %>% 
  mutate(lbl = if_else(time == max(time), as.character(Country), NA_character_)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = time, y = values, colour = geo)) +
  geom_line(size = 1) +
  geom_point(size = 2) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(2004, 2018, by = 2)) +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, 20), breaks = seq(0, 20, by = 4)) + 
  geom_label_repel(aes(label = lbl), nudge_x = 1, nudge_y = 0.5, na.rm = TRUE) +
  labs(x = "Time", y = "% of REN", title = "") +
  theme_economist() +
  theme(text = element_text(size = 11)) +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

REN contribution to Electricity, Heat and Transportation

SHP0 <- read_rds("../data/SHP0.rds")
DF <- sdg_07_40 %>% 
  filter(nrg_bal == 'REN') %>% 
  filter(time == 2017) %>% 
  inner_join(SHP0_EU, by = "geo") %>% 
  inner_join(EU, by = "geo") %>% 
  st_as_sf()

myPal  <- colorNumeric(palette = "Blues",  domain = c(0, DF$values))
LABELS <- paste0("<h3>", DF$Country, " : ", DF$values, "%</h3>") %>% 
  lapply(HTML)

MAP <- DF %>% 
  leaflet() %>% 
  setView(lng = 12.25, lat = 51.34, zoom = 4) %>% 
  addPolygons(weight = 2, color = "black",
              fillColor = ~myPal(values), fillOpacity = 0.8, label = LABELS) %>% 
  addLegend("topright", pal = myPal, values = ~values, title = "% of REN") %>% 
  addControl(html = "<small>(C) EuroGeographics for the administrative boundaries</small>", position = "bottomleft")

chartDAT <- sdg_07_40 %>%
  filter(time == 2017) %>% 
  select(geo, nrg_bal, values) %>% 
  spread(., nrg_bal, values) %>% 
  inner_join(centroids, by = "geo")
  
MAP %>% 
  addMinicharts(
    chartDAT$lng, chartDAT$lat,
    type = "pie",
    chartdata = chartDAT[, c("REN_ELC", "REN_HEAT_CL", "REN_TRA")], 
    width = 60 * sqrt(chartDAT$REN) / sqrt(max(chartDAT$REN))
  )
## Warning: Unknown or uninitialised column: 'Country'.

Closing Remarks

  • SDMX is the standard way to store and transmit statistical data, let’s use it!
  • Eurostat’s database, is fully compatible with the SDMX data format
  • Tidy tools (R) work nicely with SDMX data and offer plenty of ways for data analysis and visulation
  • Data visualisation is important, very impoertant step towards data modeling and desicion making
  • ggplot and leaflet can deal with pretty much everything about data visualisation
